    NDG outlined three deployment paths for institutions migrating to Proxmox:
  </p>

  <div class="scenarios-container">
    {scenarios.map((scenario) => (
      <div class="scenario-card">
        <div class="scenario-header">
          <div class="scenario-num">{scenario.num}</div>
          <div class="scenario-title">{scenario.title}</div>
        </div>
        <p class="scenario-desc">{scenario.description}</p>
        <div class="scenario-footer">
          <span class="best-for-label">Best for:</span>
          <span class="best-for-text">{scenario.bestFor}</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <!-- Infrastructure Requirements -->
  <h2>Infrastructure Requirements</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">
    NDG's recommended hardware specifications for NETLAB+ on Proxmox:
  </p>

  <div class="requirements-grid">
    <div class="req-card management">
      <div class="req-header">
        <span class="req-icon">&#128081;</span>
        <span class="req-title">Management Server</span>
      </div>
      <ul class="req-list">
        <li><strong>Model:</strong> Lenovo SR630 V3 (recommended)</li>
        <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 256 GB (minimum 128 GB)</li>
        <li><strong>Storage:</strong> NVMe for OS, staging pods, NETLAB-VE, PBS</li>
        <li><strong>Network:</strong> 10G NICs for cluster communication</li>
        <li><strong>Role:</strong> Staging VMs, SDK, backup server</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="req-card user">
      <div class="req-header">
        <span class="req-icon">&#128421;</span>
        <span class="req-title">User/Host Servers</span>
      </div>
      <ul class="req-list">
        <li><strong>Model:</strong> Lenovo SR630 series</li>
        <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 384-768 GB per server</li>
        <li><strong>Storage:</strong> 15 TB NVMe (masters + linked clones)</li>
        <li><strong>Network:</strong> LACP bonded 1G + dedicated 10G cluster</li>
        <li><strong>Role:</strong> Running student lab pods</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Practical Tips -->
  <h2>Practical Tips from the Workshop</h2>
  <div class="tips-container">
    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-header">
        <span class="tip-icon">&#128268;</span>
        <span class="tip-title">IPMI/iDRAC Configuration</span>
      </div>
      <p>Set up out-of-band management on a separate, segmented network. Configure BIOS for auto power-on after power failure. Critical for remote server management.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-header">
        <span class="tip-icon">&#128640;</span>
        <span class="tip-title">Use TMUX</span>
      </div>
      <p>Install and use TMUX to keep shell sessions running if your connection drops. Critical when running long installation scripts or cluster operations.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-header">
        <span class="tip-icon">&#9888;</span>
        <span class="tip-title">Don't Clone Through Proxmox</span>
      </div>
      <p>NEVER use Proxmox's default cloning for NETLAB pods. Use NETLAB's own pod management and linked clone system to maintain proper VM ID pools and configurations.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-header">
        <span class="tip-icon">&#128190;</span>
        <span class="tip-title">Storage Naming</span>
      </div>
      <p>Name storage directories NETLAB1, NETLAB2, etc. Disable preallocation on all NETLAB storage. Use consistent naming across all cluster nodes.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-header">
        <span class="tip-icon">&#128274;</span>
        <span class="tip-title">DNS for SSL</span>
      </div>
      <p>DNS must be externally resolvable if using LetsEncrypt certificates. Plan your FQDN carefully - it's hard to change later once the cluster is configured.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-header">
        <span class="tip-icon">&#9889;</span>
        <span class="tip-title">UPS Integration</span>
      </div>
      <p>Configure APC UPS Daemon or NUT (Network UPS Tools) for graceful shutdown during power failures. Essential for protecting VM data integrity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Resources -->
